  "example_section_data": {
    "children": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "value": "The following example shows the computation of a depth-first tree\nover a simple four-component graph, starting at node 0::"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "value": "     input graph          breadth first tree from (0)"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "value": "         (0)                         (0)\n        /   \\                       /   \\\n       3     8                     3     8\n      /       \\                   /       \\\n    (3)---5---(1)               (3)       (1)\n      \\       /                           /\n       6     2                           2\n        \\   /                           /\n         (2)                         (2)"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "value": "In compressed sparse representation, the solution looks like this:"
      },
      {
        "type": "code",
        "value": "from scipy.sparse import csr_matrix\nfrom scipy.sparse.csgraph import breadth_first_tree\nX = csr_matrix([[0, 8, 0, 3],\n                [0, 0, 2, 5],\n                [0, 0, 0, 6],\n                [0, 0, 0, 0]])\nTcsr = breadth_first_tree(X, 0, directed=False)\nTcsr.toarray().astype(int)"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "value": "Note that the resulting graph is a Directed Acyclic Graph which spans\nthe graph.  A breadth-first tree from a given node is unique."
      }
    ],
